Comment: The program has remained within plus or minus 10% of its cost/schedule threshold since the investment began in May 2010.  However, the EVM trend information has indicated that select projects are trending towards exceeding those thresholds. FinCEN performed an internal program review and confirmed that the BSA IT Mod technical architecture remains sound. However, based on the detailed projects review and lessons learned, there needs to be some schedule adjustments and cost realignment. One key lesson learned that is causing some of the milestones to be extended is moving from a waterfall approach to testing to a more iterative approach. FinCEN is now designing/building the system of record by BSA form then performing unit test on each form type before developing the next form. This iterative approach in the development and testing will help ensure all the business rules and data mapping is done correctly prior to data conversion.  Because of the dependency on the system of record, the Query system milestone has also shifted by two months, plus the project requires additional time to build a staging area to load all of the BSA data prior to populating the Query system. E-filing Release 2 has been broken up into three iterations, with the first being complete in December with the final dynamic or wizard version of the new SAR and CTR being complete in June 2012. The three projects that make up the Broker Information Exchange capabilities (Financial Intelligence Repository, Contact/Customer Management, and 314b) have been combined into one milestone because they will most likely share the same technology platform.  Moreover, the milestone date has shifted by one quarter in FY13 because of the budget allocation by fiscal year.Another reason for the BCR is to realign costs.  Some milestones have been complete and came in under cost, so these costs have been shifted to other, ongoing projects. Also, after a year into the Program, further cost estimating has been performed and subsequent refinements need to be made. However, there is no overall increase in the investment dollars.

Revision Reason: Replan - adding or modifying detail within the overall cost and schedule goals
Comment: FinCEN is approaching the end of the development/maintenance/enhancement or DME portion of the BSA IT Modernization four-year investment. Since May 2010, the overall Program has stayed green per Treasury schedule and cost reporting and within the 10% earned value threshold for FinCEN's cost and schedule reporting. FinCEN has completed 18 individual milestone projects, which has provided a new technical architecture and systems foundation.There is one remaining, active FY2013 project, which is to provide broker information exchange capabilities and this baseline change request (BCR) is to adjust the planned cost and schedule for this remaining effort. The requirements for the remaining DME project are tightly integrated with FinCEN's organization structure and work processes and as a result, the reorganization efforts FinCEN is currently undergoing has had an impact on the final completion date of the initial release of functionality.  These delays are necessary to allow users  to  focus their primary attention on higher priority transition team activities rather than being able to participate fully in the necessary requirements/design sessions.  In addition, the resulting transition activities will have an impact on the final organization structure, which will also require a revalidation of the current release requirements.  FinCEN is requesting this BCR to incorporate the additional time needed to capture requirements that will reflect the needs of the new organization and build in the time necessary to manage the project in parallel with FinCEN's organizational change efforts. The scope for the Broker Information Exchange project milestone originally included the full suite of capabilities to begin creating/managing/storing project work items, building a contact/customer management system, and streamlining the process for financial institutions to collaborate/share information.  As part of this BCR, FinCEN is now planning to split the original project into two releases. The first release will focus on implementing the technical Sharepoint foundation for this project and implementing functionality to first support investigative cases, which constitute roughly 85 percent of FinCEN work items and processing.   The second release will focus on delivering the information exchange functions and capabilities needed to support the remaining FinCEN processes.

The Debit Gateway seeks to rebaseline the development schedule for its next two releases, and the life cycle costs for the investment.The Debit Gateway processes electronic check and Automated Clearing House (ACH) debit transactions it receives from other FMS systems (Pay.gov, PCC OTC, OTCnet, ECP (GLN and tax lockboxes) and, eventually, EFTPS) and federal agencies. This results in the depositing of funds in the Treasury. The Gateway replaces a number of unnecessarily duplicative solutions in favor of a single, dedicated application. In so doing, the Debit Gateway benefits agencies by providing better service, and benefits FMS by doing so at a reduced cost. The Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland (FRBC) operates the Debit Gateway as Fiscal Agent.The Debit Gateway relies on commercial off-the-shelf software from the vendor U.S. Dataworks as its core. Custom code allows this COTS product to support Treasury's unique collection. Core maintenance and custom code development are currently the vendor's responsibility under contract to FRBC. In response to the vendor's financial difficulties (and, secondarily, concerns with the vendor's custom code development performance), the decision was taken in January 2012 to transition development responsibility to FRBC over a 12-18 month period. This transition will result in increased costs in FY12 and FY13 as FRBC adds resources, but ultimately produce savings once completed due to lower resource costs vs. the current vendor. Current baseline and proposed Debit Gateway lifecycle costs ($ mil.):FY12 $11.721, Proposed $12.393, Change +5.7%; FY13 $10.743, Proposed $11.790, Change +9.8%; FY14 $10.553, Proposed $9.932, Change -5.9%; FY15 $11.065, Proposed $10.546, Change -4.7%; FY16 $11.213, Proposed $9.474, Change -15.5%; FY17 $10.586, Proposed $9.572, Change -9.6%; FY18 $10.012, Proposed $9.282, Change -7.3%. Total FY12-18: $75.893, Proposed $72.990, Change -3.8%.A delay in implementing R1.4 (Adjustments, Corrections & Reversals) due to a high number of defects in vendor-delivered code has resulted in a need to delay the start and implementation of R1.5 (NACHA Rules). Delaying R1.5 permits full resource concentration on R1.4 defect correction in order to implement in production by 6-30-12. Further, the schedule for R1.6 (EFTPS) in FY13 will also change as a result before getting back to the planned schedules for Releases 1.7 (Same-day ACH processing) and 1.8 (Straight-through processing).

Comment: This BCR seeks to correct the actual costs and associated timeframes for the ISRP workstation refresh. The ISRP workstation refresh was authorized, funded and initiated last June (2010) and completed in December 2010. Due to a variety of reasons, ISRP was initially confined to reporting the FY10 costs of the Workstation Refresh against the existing FY10 Operations and Maintenance milestone, and the residual FY11 costs against the existing FY11 Operations and Maintenance milestone until such time as the new Workstation Refresh milestone could be added to the milestone plan in February 2011. By then, ISRP was locked into adding the new milestone reflecting the full, original estimated cost even though most of the actual costs had already been expended and reported in FY10. Once the Workstation Refresh BCR was uploaded to the OMB IT Dashboard in February 2011, ISRP reduced its FY11 Operations and Maintenance milestone actual costs by the amount that had been expended this FY on the workstation refresh and reported those costs ($218,496) against the newly added Workstation Refresh milestone. The changes being made with this correction BCR (a) correct (reduce) the actual costs of the FY10 Operations and Maintenance milestone by the amount of the FY10 workstation refresh actuals, (b) corrects the Workstation Refresh start dates, and (c) corrects the total actual cost and the actual percent complete for the Workstation Refresh milestone.

Comment: The purpose of this Correction BCR is to remove the Affordable Care Act (ACA) project from our baseline, because it should never have been included. Last summer when we were building our BY13 Exhibit 300 (E300), there was uncertainty as to how ACA was going to work. Our Chief Financial Officer (CFO) organization issued control charts that did not contain ACA funding saying FY2012 and FY2013 do not include ACA since we do not have the status/treatment of that program at this time. ISRP expected to do some work in support of ACA and, with the expectation they would be receiving ACA funding at some point, we created a $20K place-holder project in our E300 for ACA-related tax form changes. Then, this past January (2012), our CFO issued updated control charts depicting ACA funding being pulled out from various Exhibit 53 line items and consolidated under ACA with a transmittal message saying that the ACA funding was being consolidated. Once we realized that ISRP was not going to receive any ACA funding, the ACA place holder project in ISRP's E300 should have been removed. Based on this explanation, ISRP is now seeking Treasury's support for this Correction BCR to remove the ACA project from ISRP's baseline. We need to get this processed before our BY14 E300s are submitted to OMB so that this project isn't erroneously perpetuated in ISRP's baseline next year.

Revision Reason: Replan - adding or modifying detail within the overall cost and schedule goals
Comment: Last year, ISRP established its baseline containing a single 2012 Legislative Work Requests (WR) project with 2 activities -- Timely WRs (for $200K) and Late WRs (for $50K). We did so based on instruction to include at least 1 project in our E300 even though, at the time, we had no basis for estimating the cost of the work that was to be based on legislation that hadn't yet been issued. ISRP's legislative updates evolve into work requests only after our business partners evaluate the legislation and determine what changes need to be made. The business then submits WRs to ISRP and ISRP submits them to its contractor who subsequently provides a cost estimate for the work. If we don't know what work needs to be done, much less how much it's going to cost, we shouldn't have established a place holder project in last year's E300, and certainly not in this year's E300.Since that time, Treasury has conceded that place holder projects should not have been included in our baseline and we should have established this project only after the legislation was issued and we had meaningful basis for estimating the cost and timing of the work.   With that background in mind, this baseline change seeks to (1) delete the Late 2012 Legislative WR activity, (2) correct the planned amount and timing of the Timely 2012 Legislative WR activity, and (3) delete the Legislative Tax Form Changes project for Filing Season 2014 since it represents a place holder that should not have been included in the recent E300 submission. We will add a Filing Season 2014 Legislative Tax Form Changes project next summer after we know what work needs to be done and how much it's going to cost. In conclusion, this correction BCR is being submitted based on guidance from Treasury regarding placeholders and the need to reflect accurate planning and performance.

Comment: The purpose of this baseline change is to reduce the planned cost of Release 8 and incorporate Release 9 into our baseline.The current Release 8 (MS5) baseline includes a $3M contingency for additional hardware/software upgrades and contractor support in the event that MeF experienced any performance issues this filing season. MeF is pleased to report that the system is performing as expected and the $3M contingency is no longer needed, so the scope & associated costs are being reduced accordingly.  This baseline change seeks to incorporate Release 9 (R9) into our baseline. R9, planned for Filing Season 2014, was originally planned to add the U.S. Income Tax Return for Estates and Trusts (1041) form to the MeF environment. Last February (2012), IRS governance approved the deferral of the Employment/Tax family of forms (94x) from Release 8 and added it to Release 9. More recently, a new Return Review Program (RRP) interface was added along with additional scope to maintain system forms in compliance with IRS mandated XML standards.

Investment Description:  The Payment Application Modernization (PAM) project is an effort to standardize and modernize 30+ current mainframe based software applications that are used by the four FMS Regional Financial Centers (RFCs) and Debt Management Service (DMS) center to distribute approximately 1 billion federal payments annually. Reason for Baseline Change:  The business need for this interim BCR centers around changes in requirements and scope experienced during Production Release (PR) 3.0 including: 1) deferring the Office of Personal Management (OPM) payments from PR 3.0 and replacing with daily payments that include travel, salary and vendor, 2) changes to the Business Process Model implemented in PAM to support the variations needed for daily payments and the new standard input file format, 3) a mandate to implement certificate requirements to support Secure Hash Algorithm 2 (SHA-2), 4) development of post PR 3.0 roadmap to align with key Treasury initiatives,  5) the decision to move the application development/maintenance to the FRB resulting in the termination of  knowledge transfer activities, and 6) reporting requirements detailed in OMB M-10-25, Reforming the Federal Government's Efforts to Manage Information Technology Projects.FMS anticipates submitting another BCR within 6 to 8 months due to a possible mandate to agencies to use a standard format that will position agencies to accommodate Government Wide Accounting reporting requirements (Treasury Account Symbol/Business Event Type Code) on their detail payment records. Additionally, FMS has finalized a decision to re-purpose the Austin Financial Center (AFC) into a Debt Management Operations Center.  This will result in redistributing the AFC payment workload to the remaining three Regional Financial Centers. In addition, the inclusion of the TOP Control System (TCS) re-write effort as part of the Operation and Maintenance of RO Legacy Applications will impact the current baseline. Finally, Information Resources' (IR's) availability to support a needed upgrade of the existing DataStage product may present impacts as well due to competing  priorities and the impending release of plans for the Regional Operations Center (ROC) relocations and other Fiscal IT issues. Current vs. New Functionality:The Payment Automation Manager (PAM) application provides functionality for processing Treasury Disbursed Office (TDO) payments on behalf of FMS and Federal Program Agencies (FPAs).
To correct the zeros entered into the Actual total Cost field to a null/blank and add back activities that were excluded in the E300b XML.

Social Security Administration (SSA) and the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) announced plans to move forward with transitioning all SSA benefit and Tax payments to the PAM Standard Payment Request (SPR) to be GWA compliant by the end of 2012.  In order for PAM to be ready for the SSA and IRS transition, additional functionality that was not planned in FY 2012/2013 must now be included.  To accommodate the additions to scope, functionality originally planned must be deferred to a release beyond 2012.Implement RAD in FY 2013.  This causes a change in milestone naming convention and release schedule dates.Current vs. New Functionality:   Current PAM functionality allows agencies to send check and ACH payment requests in a standard format for IAT, PPD and CCD+ payments. PAM is a configurable application that allows the addition of the majority of agencies to process payments without making programming changes to the application.  PAM functionality will continue to be developed and implemented to meet the mandate to have functionality in place to accommodate GWA TAS/BETC reporting completed by the end of CY 2012.New 2012 functionality not in current baseline consists of 1) Generic Types of Payment Configuration Changes; 2) OFAC Screening for International Direct Deposits; 3) Agency Notification configuration moved to the RFC, Agency, and Type of Payment; 4) SSA Notification of check/Trace Numbers; 5) Redirection of Foreign Certifications to ITS.gov; 6) Debt Screening; and 7) Configure file size for TOP.Current vs. Proposed Schedule:Currently, the PAM baseline has DME activity ending on June 28, 2013 and Operation and Maintenance releases concluding on May 2, 2014. With the approval of this BCR, DME activity will be extended out to November 7, 2015. The extended development time will enable PAM to implement the additional functionality it needs to meet the new scope of the project. PAM is anticipated to reach full O&M in 2017, and costs are now projected through 2022.

The purpose of this metrics-only BCR is to (1) modify SCRIPS' Top 3 Metric mixture by exchanging our Documents Processed per Hour metric for the Percent of Tax Return Image Print Requests Fulfilled within 2 Days metric; (2) alter the reporting frequency of our Documents Processed per Hour metric from monthly to quarterly, and (3) convert the Documents Processed per Hour metric into a seasonal metric.The change being proposed to our Top 3 metrics continues to satisfy Treasury's requirement for a minimum of one Top 3 metric to be Business Results-focused and emphasizes the significance of our Print Request metric.  Providing print images to Revenue Agents (RA) and Taxpayer Service Representatives (TSR) supports IRS's Strategic Goal to enforce the law to ensure everyone meets their obligation to pay taxes.  RA's and TSR's need access to taxpayer documents, 721,825,639 of which are stored in the SCRIPS Archive Database as of 12/31/2012.  Providing the images via requests from the Integrated Data Retrieval System (IDRS) allows SCRIPS to help the IRS meet that goal.  It is also an excellent measure of the health of the SCRIPS system and its ability to accurately store, index, and retrieve taxpayer submissions.  The aforementioned changes are also due, in part, because the Docs-Per-Hour metric is difficult to compute and predict, and further complicated by a seasonal complexity.

Revision Reason: Rebaseline - scope and objectives evolve due to incremental or iterative system development
Comment: In March 2012, IRS governance authorized the provision of funding to support a critically needed technical refreshment of SCRIPS system components. Funding for the entire suite of hardware, software and support services was estimated to be $6.347M which included a replacement of the NetApp work-in-progress storage, as well as EMC Centera long-term storage. Given the length of time from approval to identification of the solution, standards changed and the IRS entered into an Enterprise Shared Storage (ESS) system contract that provided for a new solution to the SCRIPS storage requirements. This BCR seeks to incorporate the associated changes to the scope, schedule and cost into the SCRIPS Exhibit 300 baseline.

Revision Reason: Rebaseline - scope and objectives evolve due to incremental or iterative system development
Comment: The IRS entered into the Enterprise Shared Storage (ESS) system contract that includes a new solution to the SCRIPS storage requirements.  The original deployment dates were to run from August 19 through December 4, 2013.It was determined that we needed to move the refresh date to coincide with the SCRIPS Server Refresh dates to run from January 6 through March 24, 2014 for the following reasons:     Cost prohibitive to put the ESS on the old servers as we would have had to upgrade their operating system.     Timing constraints to have the site preparation work done and the new servers moved to be co-located with the ESS equipment.A fallback plan is in place where if any of the sites cannot be upgraded timely for whatever reason, we will move that site startup in to the month of May; bypassing April due to peak processing.

Revision Reason: Replan - planned change with minimal change in overall scope, cost or schedule objectives
Comment: The CBIS project is requesting a rebaseline as a formal reprogram that will affect the overall cost and schedule but will not alter the scope of work to be performed. The rebaseline or formal reprogramming request is to due the removal QASP or incentive fee payments from the performance measurement baseline, the award of the PMO support vendor contract and the approval of funding previously on hold for the system integrator to complete Phase 1, Release 3 and Phase 2 activities.

The CBIS investment is changing to the current cost, schedule, and performance baselines to reflect the removal of Phase II tasks and activities specific to Trust Funds.  These baseline changes affect 6 of the CBIS milestone activities reflected in eCPIC and in the agency s Earned Value Management systems.   On December 21, 2010, OPM (in concert with OMB) placed an indefinite hold on the implementation of Phase II of CBIS.  Additionally, 4 Phase 1 Milestones are being revised as a result of this baseline change request. These milestones were incorrectly marked complete based on date of last activity, but have since been noted as not complete. These milestones are dependent on OPM negotiations with Accenture on the pricing for the remaining Release 3 specifically Call 11 tasks.  Contract pricing in place, but no new requisition has yet been established. As a result of removing the 6 Milestones associated with Phase 2, the current CBIS baseline will decrease. The new baseline will only include the remaining Phase 1 and Other Support Milestones. Cost : The changes requested include removing 3 milestones, and issuing a stop work and close on the 3 milestones which have actual dollars for a total of $41M from the Phase 2 Planned Baseline. Schedule: The changes requested include removing work associated with the Phase 2 Planned Baseline within the 12/2009   07/2018 timeframe which included both DME and O&M milestones.  This is a correction type rebaseline.  The Dashboard counts this is a separate rebaseline event even though there one rebaseline approved by the CIO for both the correction changes and the rebaseline changes.

Investment Title: Human Resources Line of Business (HR LOB)
Comment: The reason for the rebaseline request is that the HR LOB updated our planning and government FTE costs for FY 2013 and 2014 to reflect our current budget spreadsheet, but our total costs remained the same for both fiscal years. Total costs for FY 2015 through FY 2021 incorporate an inflation factor to the appropriated costs. (The partner contributions to HRLOB remain flat.) Milestones were updated based on input from our primary governing body, the Multi-Agency Executive Strategy Committee (MAESC). Updated operational performance measures that align with investment milestones needed to be provided as well. Operational performance indicators and performance targets were revised to support the updated performance measures and provide an appropriate measure of the HR LOB's progress.This rebaseline is summarized below:a. Cost Planning and government FTE costs were updated to match our investment itemized budget spreadsheets, but our bottom line total costs stayed the same.b. Schedule Milestones (FY 2013/2014) were updated to ensure that a complete view of all investment milestones were included.c. Performance measures Operational performance measures were updated to align with investment milestones and provide measurable results.d. Performance indicators Operational performance indicators were updated to align with the revised performance measures.e. Performance targets Operational performance targets were updated to align with the revised performance measures.

Investment Title: Health Claims Data Warehouse and Analysis (HCDW)
Comment: Initially, the HCDW project was limited to providing OPM with the capacity to collect, store, and analyze health claims from the Federal Employee Health Benefits (FEHB) Program. In early to mid August, the scope was increased, primarily brought by the passage of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act (PPACA) to include: Extending the enrollment for the FEHB Program to include employees of federally recognized Native American Tribes and Tribal Organizations; Pre-Existing Conditions Insurance (PCI) Program; and Multi-State Option Program (beginning in January 2014).  These three programs increase system complexity and requirements that far exceeded the original plan.

Investment Title: Health Claims Data Warehouse and Analysis (HCDW)
Comment: Change in acquisition strategy from GSA Schedule to Full & Open competition has significantly delayed the acquisition schedule. This change in acquisition strategy has also resulted in changes in the Project and Acquisition Management Plans, which have been adjusted to reflect the additional time needed to adequately address the milestone changes that have occurred. The Health Claims Data Warehouse (HCDW) is currently in the final planning phase of the acquisition lifecycle, and continues to develop requirements. The scope expansion necessitates the continued re-analysis of risk and requires the program to rebaseline.  HCDW is working to become part of the OIG s FEHBP Data Warehouse and will utilize their existing architecture and technology standards. This change will lower the overall development costs through the use of shared resources and processes and should result in a more reliable product because proven processes will be used. The project team continues to coordinate closely with the CIO's staff to ensure appropriate compliance. This Program is in its infancy and has an inherent level of uncertainty and high level of future development.     The HCDW revised system of records notice (SORN) internal and external review period has been lengthy resulting in a delay to continue the acquisition process, which impacts all future milestones. The HCDW Project remains on hold pending OMB and OPM Director approval of the revised SORN.  OPM first published a system of records notice pertaining to the Health Claims Data Warehouse on October 5, 2010 with the comment period closing November 15, 2010.  On November 15, 2010, OPM extended the comment period to December 15, 2010 and indicated its intent to modify certain aspects of the system of records notice.  On December 15, 2010, OPM published a notice closing the comment period and announced that a revised notice would be published. The revised SORN is currently under review by OMB and HHS. It is anticipated that the revised SORN will be published in the Federal Register sometime March 2011.The revised baseline more accurately represents a realistic and achievable set of milestones.  Additional milestones will be added following completion of the acquisition lifecycle.

EHRI operates largely on a fee-for-service basis. As a result, the Program s funding is highly dependent on partner agencies  ability to fund our services.  Therefore, milestones for these services in FY11 and FY12 are based on forecasts using the latest information from partner agencies and will require revision as funding is identified.

Note: This baseline event is intended to bring EHRI's IT Dashboard milestones in line with its EVM baseline.  OPM used a separate Earned Value Management (EVM) tool and process to closely manage investments that spend money in development of new functionality.  The FY2011 Continuing Resolution has impacted EHRI customer agencies' ability to fund new eOPF implementations under EHRI's fee-for-service funding model. As a result, several agencies that were planned for FY2011 have not moved forward and have to be removed from EHRI's baseline.  These agencies include the Department of Defense, Department of Interior, and the Department of the Treasury.Also, under review is EHRI's funding for the Data Warehouse (DW). Historically, the steady state milestone covering DW hosting, operations and maintenance was aligned with EHRI's appropriation. This re-baseline event, however, brings the DW hosting, operations and maintenance milestone in line with the program's EVM baseline.The impact of Agencies not implementing eOPF in FY11 is decreased planned costs in the following milestones:Fee-for-Service - FY2011 Hosting, Operations and MaintenanceFee-for-Service - FY2011 eOPF Implementation -  DoD (partial), Treasury (partial)Fee-for-Service - FY2011 ePower LicensesThe planned cost for the Data Warehouse Production Operations and Maintenance FY2011 milestone is now aligned with EHRI's EVM baseline. There is no impact to EHRI's budget.

Revision Reason: Replan - planned change with minimal change in overall scope, cost or schedule objectives
Comment: The rebaseline change that was previously submitted to the Dashboard on 3/1/2011 was discovered to have some entry errors that did not make all of the intended changes.  This rebaseline is a correction to the previous 3/1/2011 rebaseline that was to change the funding strategy.                                                     The purpose of this BCR is twofold. First, it brings EHRI's Information Technology (IT) Dashboard milestones in line with its existing Fiscal Year (FY) 2011 earned value management (EVM) baseline. Second, it revises EHRI's FYI2 milestones to be consistent with the Program's Budget Year 2012 appropriated funding passback from the Office of Management & Budget (OMB). These changes do not reflect problems with the investment.                                             The overall impact of this change is to add the initial baseline to the Dashboard and to make reductions to the EHRI spending because EHRI has not received funding from the partner agencies for the associated eOPF implementations, there have been no commitments made by EHRI to any partner agency or contractor. If the partner agencies are unable to secure funding for the eOPF project in the next several months, it will present challenges to both EHRI and partner agencies in meeting stated OPM and OMB performance goals. Additionally, delays in funding may force EHRI scanning vendors to close their facilities and lay off their employees.

The EPIC Transformation investment is requesting a rebaseline for FY2011 through the end of the project. This rebaseline provides better definition in the planned budget, schedules and approach and is in alignment with the OMB Memorandum M-10-27 and Federal IT Dashboard.The changes provide a positive impact to ensure the project is proceeding within acceptable thresholds, providing solid planned budget and schedule, while minimizing risk to the production environment.Specifically, we are requesting the following changes:     Increase the Exhibit 300 cost figures for FY12 by 16.5% from the approved baseline projections; increase FY13 - FY16 costs by 3-5% above the proposed FY12 costs. See attached cost spreadsheets for original summary of funding, proposed re-baseline, and cost variance.     Reallocate Development Modernization and Enhancement (DME) costs to Steady State (SS) from FY09 - FY16 to more accurately reflect the nature of USA Staffing operation and maintenance activities.    Add DME costs for Onboarding Manager, which is an expansion of functionality to facilitate the on-boarding process.   Onboarding Manager will be developed and piloted in two phases.  Phase I will be implemented in FY11; Phase II in FY12.    Modify SS and DME milestones for FY11.  Add SS milestones for the period FY11 - FY16 and DME milestones for FY11 - FY12.    Update the FY11 - FY12 performance measures and added performance measures for FY13 - FY16 that are in-line with those that USA Staffing is currently tracking in the four measurement areas: customer results; mission and business results; technology; and processes and activities. These measures would replace the broad Human Resources Solutions (HRS) measures.This rebaseline change was approved by the OPM CIO.

Comment: This rebaseline is for the purpose of properly identifying the DME and SS cost and schedule performance data for both the Recruitment One-Stop FY 2010-11 and the USAJOBS 3.0 FY11-12 projects.  Currently, all project costs and milestone schedule performance dates on the current Cost and Schedule Performance Table in eCPIC are categorized as DME.  This is incorrect and needs to be corrected, so that cost and schedule performance data is reflected for both DME and SS activities for these two investments.The overall impact is that the information presented in eCPIC would be correctly categorized for these two projects within the investment.  The cost and schedule performance can be more accurately recorded and tracked between DME and SS related project activities with these changes.Since this re-baseline would simply re-categorize project related costs from all DME to a mixture of DME and SS for both investments, with no net impact to either investment's bottom line project cost, there would be no impact to either investment's ability to meet contractual obligations or on current planned project scope delivery.  Nor would there be any impact to project timelines.

This rebaseline is a correction to the Exhibit 300B data previously submitted to the Dashboard in September 2011.  During the Exhibit 300 submission the USAJOBS investment had one activity that had a zero instead of a null in the total actual cost field.  This rebaseline is removing the zero and replacing the cost with a null on the Dashboard for one activity not yet completed.  OMB guidance on the subject is:   Note that if left uncorrected, the zero actual costs will mean that an extreme variance for this activity will be calculated, since with actual costs left at zero, the Dashboard records this as an actual cost of zero for the activity in question, and ignores any projected final cost.  If the field is left as a null, however, the Dashboard will take the projected final cost as the operative value to use in any variance calculations.

This baseline change will result in no change to the existing system functionality.PROJECT 1 - Mid-Year 2013 (MY13):The EFDS MY13 project is designed to incorporate DME and Maintenance work (decoupled change requests and Production defects) associated with the previous Filing Season (FS13).  This project contains one activity phase. PROJECT 2 - Filing Season 2014 (FS14):The EFDS FS14 project is designed to incorporate DME and Maintenance work (change requests, legislative changes, and Production defects) associated with the upcoming Filing Season (FS14).  This project contains two activity phases.

Revision Reason: Replan - adding or modifying detail within the overall cost and schedule goals
Comment: Upon reviewing all of the requirements for RRP, the project team's evaluation concluded that the work required to deliver Transition State (TS) 2 exceeded their capacity. Alternative solutions were considered and presented to the Revenue Protection Technology (RPT) governance bodies.  They voted for joint functionality between EFDS and RRP TS2 for 2015 and postponed the full replacement of EFDS until 2016. The updated scope of EFDS includes an interim release to provide the Business with some automation until the mission critical functionality of RRP can be delivered in 2016. Due to the change, EFDS is requesting to rebaseline the program plan.

This baseline change is in response to the OMB TechStat on RMSS, 6/29/12, and the Post-TechStat Corrective Actions memo on 8/3/12. In that memo Reclamation was tasked with the following: developing a project plan and roadmap for RMSS by 8/23/12; having a draft Exhibit 300 of RMSS by 9/6/12; and finalizing the Exhibit 300 and 53 information for RMSS by 10/10/12. This baseline change will align the roadmap/project plan information to the Exhibit 300 project activities table in time for the 10/10/12 due date for the final x300 and x53. Please note, total lifecycle costs have been reduced slightly due to better estimation of cost of living adjustments for labor costs. These numbers are reflective of the adjusted figures (after BY13 passback) that accounted for FTE cost of living adjustments instead of applying a flat budget across fiscal years.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Revision Reason: Replan - adding or modifying detail within the overall cost and schedule goals
Comment: Overall, adding, modifying and deleting project activities based on reduced FY2013 funding.  Several planned start dates have been changed to align with actual task order or contract award dates that were modified to accurately reflect procurement timelines.More specifically, Counterparty Management project activities are being realigned and expanded to support potential decommissioning of legacy systems.Deployment of Federal Financial Services Platform (FFSP) - Infrastructure GEN2 activities have been deleted as these functions will be transferred to HUD OCIO as part of the existing HITS infrastructure contract.An additional project activity has been added for the Physical Inspections Alignment initiative while consolidating phases of the original alignment project.Activities for the Healthcare project have been consolidated with the MFH Automated Underwriting System due to similar project requirements.  Later phases of this effort will encompass configuration activities which can be leveraged by multiple program areas.Changes to existing project activities cost, schedule and scope are minimal.  Overall, the reduced funding amount in FY2013 will significantly extend the program completion date thus limiting FHA's ability to leverage the initial investment made to obtain a modern technology platform to support migration of legacy systems and applications.

Investment Title: DOI - IBC FMLoB Shared Service Provider
Comment: Updates to metrics during BY14 Official Submission.

As a Shared Service Center, our mission is to provide standardized services as well as offer new services to Federal agencies.  This provides cost avoidance and economies of scale.  Often, these services are agreed to after the budget submission, which means our revenue (and thus our costs) increase.  To provide accurate reporting, we need to rebaseline each year, based on previous years' W2s for each bureau or agency.  Additionally, the WCF Consortium usually does not make its decisions until after Exhibit 300 submission deadlines, causing disconnects.   FY10:  Anticipated revenue and customers for DME did not materialize. Department requested NBC concentrate on current offerings.  DME planned baseline is less; SS is a bit higher.FY11:  Additional services but budget cut by Department.  SS is lower.FY12:  Significant increase in anticipated clients, which increases revenues and costs (as a fee for service provider).  SS planned baseline increase.

Investment Title: NOAA/NWS/ Next Generation Air Transportation System (NextGen)
Comment: Replan impacting tables B.1 and B.2 due to reduced FY12 appropriation from FY12 request.  Also re-organized the structure of the program to align with the program WBS and improve traceability and visibility into program performance.Reduction of planned funding from FY12 Budget Request profile to actual current profile has delayed the Initial Operational Capability of the NextGen 4-D Weather Data Cube by one year to 2015.  This new timeline, coordinated with the FAA provides adequate time for the FAA to finalize their system development for their IOC, which is also delayed until March 2016.Funding appropriated and approved in FY12 and FY13, respectively, represents a reduction of approximately 50% from planned program funding.  This reduction prevents NOAA from progressing towards meeting objectives for improved weather data and accuracy by postponing investments in improved numerical modeling and statistical guidance, weather research and development, human forecast tools, and forecast performance assessment.  In addition, there will be less investment and progress towards enhancing the consistency of weather forecast information through implementation of a single authoritative source capability.  This reallocation of program activities will delay the date for forecast accuracy improvements for Mid-Operational Coability (MOC) by three years from 2018 to 2021.Summary of Funding Table adjustments were made to clarify the budget.

DOC has requested an increase of funding in FY 2012 for Census, NIST and NOAA (funding for NOAA has been requested through a NOAA-specific infrastructure budget) to purchase a standard Oracle/Sun Solaris technology platform for the CBS test, development and production instances.  This will allow for the standardization of the CBS operating system and hardware platform.  In 2005, the CBS Executive Board conducted a business case and initiated a CBS consolidation effort to standardize the CBS technology platform, including efforts to co-locate the CBS and its associated environments at a single location, the Census Data Center (CDC) in 2008.  However, this project was redirected as a result of changes in the Census Bureau s priorities due to unforeseen issues with the Decennial Census.  Several decennial systems were moved to the CDC resulting in a power supply issue that forced the CBS servers to move out of the CDC.   As a result, the bureaus stopped their migration efforts and reverted back to their respective data centers using their current infrastructures that were near the end of life and/or capacity.  For example, two bureaus (Census and NOAA) reverted back to operating on Tru64 Operating Systems for Alpha Server Platforms and HP support ends in December 2012.  If the equipment and operating system is not purchased, there will be a significant impact on the continuity of operations for DOC s financial system, significantly increase the risk of system interruption and security exposure over time.

Revision Reason: Rebaseline - current baseline is no longer useful as a management tool
Comment: This investment required a baseline change due to changes in the internal reporting requirements at HUD. In an effort to improve visibility, HUD has changed its Ex. 300B   Table B.1 reporting level from the major initiative level down to the project level. This change will increase the level of detail that is provided on the Federal IT Dashboard, as well as help comply with OMB s 6-month project interval requirement. These changes require a baseline change on the dashboard.The performance metrics for this investment have been redefined for CY13 to more adequately reflect the goals of this investment. These changes require a baseline change on the IT Dashboard.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Revision Reason: Rebaseline - other reason consistent with agency policy and M-10-27
Comment: Re-baseline is required for multiple reasons. For all HEARTH-eGrants projects, a new contract award for executing these projects was protested in June 2012. This required significant re-plan within the portfolio. The protest was resolved in November 2012 and a new award was made. At that time the Investment Manager learned for the first time the details of the new contract ceiling, which is now controlled annually at the system level instead of the portfolio level. In many cases this ceiling structure conflicted with and would not support the planned cost of projects in this Investment. Therefore resources and scope for the projects had to be realigned within the portfolio in order to work within these constraints. Additional rationale for re-baseline varies by Project:Energy and Performance Information Center (EPIC) Spring 2013 Release 3, eGrants-eSnaps System Release #2: Scope and Objective evolve due to iterative system development. This project has been re-planned under a managed change control process. Hearth-eGrants-GMP System Release #1 and Hearth-eGrants-IDIS System Release #2: Adding detail within overall Cost and Schedule goals. These projects may now be decomposed to a finer level of detail to show milestones or Usable Functionalities, along with associated Costs and Schedule. Hearth-eGrants-eSnaps System Release #1: Modifying detail within overall Cost and Schedule goals. During the course of iterative software development, two Usable Functionalities were removed from scope under managed change control process, and the plan updated / project re-baselined. Specifically, these two functionalities could not be completed due to pending OMB approval of HEARTH Competitive Homeless assistance grant regulations. These factors are outside of HUD s control. Hearth-eGrants-GMP System Release #2, Hearth-eGrants-IDIS System Release #3, and Hearth-eGrants-eSnaps System Release #3: Scope and Cost evolve due to iterative system development, and due to Significant Contract change (see contract ceiling discussion above). Specifically, HUD must decrease planned scope and budgets on these three projects and redistribute resources within the portfolio to accommodate the funding limits defined by the contract ceilings for each of these three systems.

Investment Title: Foreign Assistance Coordination and Tracking System (FACTS)
Revision Reason: Rebaseline - scope and objectives evolve due to incremental or iterative system development
Comment: Beginning in FY13, the FACTS Program will initiate the development for the next generation system.  FACTS Info's original architecture was developed to support a data warehouse; it was not designed or built in a modular expandable architecture to easily support all functionality that is currently being developed in it.  To avoid any potential risk related to FACTS Info's scalability, the FACTS Program will initiate a next generation project in FY13. This next generation system will be more flexible and scalable in order to adapt to the changing requirements of foreign assistance budgeting.  FACTS is looking to utilize the cloud's infrastructure-as-a-service model in the next generation. Development of the next generation system is currently scheduled from FY13-FY16.  FACTS Info will run in tandem with the next generation system. As modules are deployed in the new system, they will be shut down in FACTS Info.  The plan is for the FACTS Info system to be fully shutdown as the new system moves to O&M.

Investment Title: NTIA - Radio Spectrum Management - Federal Spectrum Management System (FSMS)
Comment: This budget change request to modify the 2009 established baseline extends the FSMS development, modernization, or enhancement DME schedule by 2 years to 9/30/2015, increasing Planning and DMEcosts from $23,320K to $46,004K. The request extends operations and maintenancefrom 5 years to 15 years, adding in steady state, and now runs through 2026, increasingO&M from $8,664K to $39,587K. This increases the total budget for the projectedlifecycle of the investment from $31,984K to $85,591K.B-1 Projects Table. Added historical (Project ID 7312M1100) and future (Project IDs 7312M1103 and 7312M1104) projects so that eCPIC reflects the full scope of the FSMS Planning and DME from 2003 to 2015. Reduced planned cost of Project ID 7312M1101 by 10.4K, and reduced planned cost of Project ID 7312M1102 by 86.998K to reflect adjustments made as a result of the 2012 Independent Government Cost Estimate. Note the following differences from the 2009 baseline: a) Cost of 7312M1101 (FSMS Phase 01) increased by 1,590K due to increased gov't level of effort, and additional hardware and software infrastructure requirements; b)Cost of 7312M1102 (FSMS Phase 2) increased by 8,076K due to movement of most frequency proposal back office scope from Release 3 to Release 2, additional hardware, software, and data standardard definition requirements, and additional government integration requirements; c) Cost of 7312M1103 (FSMS Phase 3) increased by 3,582K due to additional hardware and software requirements, and the movement of work from government to contractor FTEs to mitigate risks to product quality, project schedule, and the achievement of business objectives; and d) Cost of 7312M1104 (FSMS Phase 4) increased by 3,154K due to additional hardware and software requirements, and the movement of work from government to contractor FTEs to mitigate risks to product quality, project schedule, and the achievement of business objectives.B-2 Master Cost and Schedule Table. This table is revised in full to provide a granular view of project activities in 1-3 month increments, to facilitate transparency. The details have been adjusted from 2009 baseline and the October 2012 BCR to reflect adjustments made as a result of the Indepentent Government Cost Estimate and Risk Mitigations.

The reasons for re-baseline are two fold:  to cancel all future activities of the Corrections and Adjustment project and adding a new project for Dynamic Split functionality. With the cancellation of the Corrections and Adjustment project in February, 2012, all future activities for Corrections and Adjustment project have been deactivated and focus has shifted to optimization and conversion needs. The shift in focus have resulted in reallocation of some 2012 and 2013 DME buget to O&M. Also, several Agencies have expressed a strong interest in entering C-Key information at the summary level of check processing for end of day processing to be fully compliant with government wide accounting requirement by 2014 that has resulted in the addition of the Dynamic Split project.

This Baseline Change Request (BCR) form is being submitted based on guidance by CPIC to revise the OTCnet Performance Metrics. Four Metrics were deleted, two new metrics were added, and three metrics were revised. Also, the Project Life Cycle Cost for the Corrections and Adjustment Project was not reflected properly to add up to the 3 Activity Levels for the project. Per my discussion with the Help Desk, corrections have been made to the following information for the Corrections and Adjustment Project: Project Description, Project Life Cycle Cost and Project Completion Date.

Revision Reason: Rebaseline - other reason consistent with agency policy and M-10-27
Comment: Based on a full program level review of cost, schedule and priorities, in Q1 2013, Fiscal service has made a decision to postpone the Dynamic Split project to a later date and address Archiving/Architectural changes and Supporting Straight through Processing (STP) as priorities for OTCnet. Archiving and architectural changes became a critical need to minimize operational risk of the system by creating an Archive database and separating Online Transaction Processing (OLTP)  from historical information. Archiving Project is broken up into Phase 1 for Check Processing and Phase 2 for Deposit Processing and Reports. Supporting Straight through Processing became a priority as it will provide an improved cash position for the Treasury on a daily basis through a streamlined Routing Transit Number (RTN) process. OTCnet has a number of changes to support this project including reporting Treasury RTN numbers, identifiying NAF RTN number and processing adjustment/corrections and rescinds  (ACRs) from Debit Gateway. STP Changes will support FRB CashLink decommissioning. STP project will also be broken up in 2 segments: near term and full solution with ACR processing. A placeholder project for replanning Dynamic TAS project has been added in 2015.

Due to the results of our alternative analysis and a need to better align our business activities within the E-300, the following changes are being made to the FY12 FFAS baseline:- Removed DME 2 - ETS2 Contract - GSA has been unable to meet the award deadline for the new ETS contract due to protests on the master contract award.  Therefore, it is estimated that this project will be delayed until FY13.- Removed DME 4 - Contract Writing System - The contract for the new Procurement Contract Writing System was awarded to our current vendor (Compusearch).  Therefore, the milestone for transitioning to a new procurement/contract writing system is no longer required.- Added a Consolidated DME as these components are being managed as one project which includes:  a. DME 1 (R12)  b. DME 3 (Oracle Projects Module)  c. Removed costs associated with US Mint core financial system upgrade to R-12 due to customer requested delay.  d. Added estimated costs associated with US Mint SaaS project integration.In addition, the reductions to the original DME#1 reflects a delay in the US Mint instance upgrade due to a new US Mint priority (the US Mint has requested our assistance in integrating a new Software-as-a-Service (SAAS) solution for their Integrated Retail Information System (IRIS) with our Oracle E-Business Suite).  This was identified by US Mint as their highest priority and thus we have delayed upgrading their core financial system until this project is completed (currently expecting FY13).

The CAII program went through a series of events within the various projects that all occurred within a 6 month time period after we submitted the original cost and milestone data.  These events along with the DHS requirements for shorter, more descriptive milestones left us with the opportunity to make changes that would not only be easier to track due to shorter milestone lengths but also much easier for the Project Managers to determine the dollar allocations toward milestones on their projects based on the contract fiscal year.  The PMO support team also discovered financial data that had not been incorporated into actuals for closed milestones from 2008/2009.  This required the modification of planned and actual dollars for milestone #1. The modifications made caused minimal change in the overall scope of CAII and its projects, no change in the overall planned dollar for the full lifecycle of the program occurred, and there were minimal schedule changes on the individual project level. A few reasons for the rebaseline:- The development of ACRIMe release 2.0 has fallen behind.  Due to this schedule delay ACRIMe has modified their mix of resource and the deliverables have changed or been extended.  - Secure Communities priorities have focused SDS resources to work on ACRIMe development deliverables.  This has caused the SDS dates and costs to be slightly re-planned.  - ATP milestone descriptions were changed to allow the PM to easily and accurately report on all costs.

Over the last several months, ICE/OCIO has been instituting changes to the ACRIMe Modernization project to counter significant issues in requirements gathering, poor developer performance and inadequate contract control and project management processes that have led to schedule and cost overruns. OCIO has assigned new project and portfolio managers in the last 12 months, has hired a new development contractor and strengthened contract controls. The ACRIMe Modernization project has also shifted its development methodology from a waterfall to Agile methodology, co-locating system users with developers leading to direct interaction that is key to proper product development. Functionality is being built in much smaller modules, leading to a vastly increased number of releases. A much tighter relationship with the business owner has led to a reprioritization of the releases, enabling the ACRIMe project to provide greater business value earlier than initially planned. To assist with greater flexibility in development of both the ACRIMe and Status Determination Services projects, ICE/OCIO is in the process of developing new contract vehicles that will enable it to more rapidly issue short task orders to develop modules of the larger applications. Delays in the procurement process have added to the schedule overruns, necessitating additional slippage in the overall ACRIMe Project schedule. The schedules initially placed into the project execution tab were the best plan available when the CAII OMB 300 schedule was developed. The changes made reflect changes in project prioritization, functionality needs, and expectations of contract vehicle availability. Even though project schedules have been extended, overall costs are expected to remain within +/-8% of original estimates, largely due to shorter development cycles and savings generated through tighter integration of developers with business users.

The USA Staffing Program requests approval to change the IT Investment baseline for USA Staffing to ensure that the cost, milestones and performance measures most precisely reflect future plans.  This change in baseline will best reflect the direction of the USA Staffing program based on the most recent trends in Federal hiring, the latest information about customer needs, and growth in the USA Staffing customer base.  The FY12-FY16 cost projections have increased to reflect a growing USA Staffing customer base.  The USA Staffing program has seen unprecedented growth within its customer base over the last year.  In FY11, USA Staffing expanded it scope to include an enterprise-wide agreement with the Department of Defense and the Department of Health and Human Services.  In addition, the Department of Veterans Affairs expanded its use of USA Staffing to include Merit Promotion Hiring.  As a result, USA Staffing is processing between 500,000 to 600,000 employment applications each month.  This growth in the USA Staffing program necessitates broader SS activities in FY12 and beyond to ensure sufficient infrastructure to support a government-wide customer base.  The Exhibit 300 was updated to reallocate DME costs to SS to more accurately reflect the nature of operation and maintenance activities.  USA Staffing is a mature, stable system that is fully operational within 51 Federal agencies.  The USA Staffing system has maintained continuous operability, availability, and cost-recovery status for more than 10 years.  The changes were made to reflect a greater understanding within the USA Staffing Program Office on regulations and policies within Exhibit 300 and Exhibit 53.  The changes are a more accurate picture of our current state and contain metrics that are more appropriate and consistent with DME and SS operations for a mature system fully operational system.  The changes also reflect the need to build infrastructure overtime to adequately support a significant expansion of the USA Staffing customer base. With an expanded customer base, USA Staffing is able to further distribute its fixed costs creating government-wide efficiencies and cost savings.  As a result, USA Staffing will retain its current pricing in FY12. There are no contract implications associated with the rebaseline as USA Staffing is managed primarily with Federal employees and individual contractors.  USA Staffing revolving fund agreements will cover all planned expenses.

Comment: The Human Resources Automated Services Investment (HRAS) is performing a rebaseline in order to reflect project and program updates to their Ex. 300A&B. An OMB TechStat was recently called for this investment, and resulted in constructive criticisms of the business case that were incorporated into these updates. Areas of the Ex. 300A that were updated include out year funding requests, IPT membership, and investment details. These changes serve to best illustrate the health of this investment and future plans for improving the HR program. We also updated the Ex. 300B Project information to reflect recent restructuring of the HR End-to-End initiative. HR End-to-End has been broken up into five projects in the Ex. 300B, B.1 Table, with their associated major tasks and milestones in the B.2 Table. These required re-baseline changes provide a much clearer view of the HRAS Investment (HUD Information Human Resources Training System and HR End-to-End initiative).

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Comment: The Human Resources Automated Services Investment (HRAS) is performing a rebaseline in order to reflect project and program updates to their Exhibit 300A&B. As a result of feedback from a June 1, 2012 TechStat, further detail and revision was incorporated in to the Exhibit 300A&B.  Project information in the Exhibit 300A was updated to show more accurate information in regards to previous year funding as well as out-year funding requests to include the decommissioning of legacy systems. These changes were made to provide a more accurate representation of the funding of the HRAS investment over time that will demonstrate cost savings. Additionally, the Exhibit 300B Project Information was updated due to the fact that the project team has progressed further through the project planning and management lifecycle for each of the HR End-to-End Projects. Changes to the B.1 and B.2 tables were made as a result of the ability to better project start and completion dates, provide additional tasks and associated timelines for completion, provide more accurate cost information and reflect work that has been completed. Updates to the Exhibit 300 will provide a current view of the HRAS Investment to include the HR End-To-End Initiative.

As a result,the the implementation of the remaining Schedules in the project plan were placed in containment. Investment Title: FAAXX803: NextGen R&D Collaborative Air Traffic Management (CATM)
Comment: This is not a re-baseline. NextGen CATM is in the planning phase and has not been baselined. The solution sets include pre-acquisition activities scoped by individual projects designed to inform operational and technical requirements. The concept and the requirements maturity is used to inform acquisition decisions. When the FAA makes a decision to acquire new systems, those acquisitions are represented in their individual OMB-300s . Therefore, the information in the solution set OMB-300s represents the planned pre-implementation activities for the applicable timeframe. Due to the incremental development approach, designed to reduce overall programmatic risk, the solution set OMB-300s are planning in nature and will remain in planning. Section II.B milestones have been updated to reflect funding changes as of January 7, 2011. Milestones have also been broken out into greater detail consistent with FAA plans to improve milestone clarity and transparency.

The original AoA for a DoD solution was slated to be completed by end of March 2011. However, based on direction from the White House and consistent with congressional intent, it was decided that the EHR Way Ahead solution will be a joint solution between DoD and VA. As a result of the meeting on 3/17/11 between the Secretary of Defense and Secretary of Veterans Affairs, the AoA work has been extended to accommodate for the new EHR Way Ahead.

The Integrated Electronic Health Record (iEHR) (a follow on to originally proposed Electronic Health Record Way Ahead) is designed to provide a comprehensive, longitudinal, electronic health record that is available anytime and anywhere for the lifetime of the patient. Since the original Electronic Health Record Way Ahead (EHR WA) has now become a joint DoD/VA program, iEHR has received an Acquistion Decision Memorandum and is now an official DoD program. Rebaseline is to close out EHR WA and insert new projects, activities, and risk for the iEHR.

Comment: The total estimated cost in FY11-16 for NSI increased $54.8M from the previous baseline. The additional $54.8M funds includes supplemental FY 2010 made available in the USPTO Supplemental Appropriations Act of 2010 (Public Law 111-224) and FY 2011-2016 funds that were previously allocated to  Miscellaneous and General Expenses (MGE),  but included such IT-related items as telecommunication circuits. After the initial NSI baseline was submitted, further internal review resulted in additional supplemental and MGE costs being re-allocated to the NSI budget, to properly report them as IT expenses. This major increase resulted in significant changes to the estimated costs for many NSI milestones. Additional changes from the initial baseline include: (1) reducing FTE costs to account for a Congressional decision to freeze pay for federal workers in FY 11 and FY12, and (2) adding milestones for prior year programs that were not included in the initial baseline, but have incurred expenses in FY 11 that need to be reported.

Investment Title: IT Infrastructure End User Services and Support (EUSS)
Comment: This is the first year that we are reporting against infrastructure investment project performance and our planning process still needs to mature.  While the two projects hit their cost targets, we initially failed to consider how the large volume of changes would affect our user community.  We chose to extend deployment to alleviate the impacts to our users rather than impact them with multiple changes all at once.  In the future, we will ensure that there is limited overlap between projects that affect the user community directly and allow for significantly more time when deploying functionality directly to them.  We held a bureau level TechStat on February 22, 2012, which identified the following issues in our planning process:-We realized the complexity of OTS integration as it became more apparent that the dates for deploying Blackberry devices and MIPS had to be moved out to accommodate higher priority integration issues.  We learned that going forward we will need to add additional time to our project plan for projects dealing with end user groups.  -Brief multiple integration stakeholders early in the project planning process to discuss similar projects across ITS to promote awareness.-Improving oversight and ensure completion of the project on schedule and within cost.Therefore, we are requesting approval of this baseline change request to reflect the conscious decision to delay deployment.Also added the total to the Target CY for the Blackberry Enterprise Server (BES) Availability metric and updated the comment sections of the metrics.

Based on meetings with the GWA business users, agency users, and other relevant stakeholders senior management has determined that the CARS investment needs to accommodate additional scope to successfully transition reporting and auditing features to the CARS system after the decommissioning of STAR.  CARS will continue to work to complete all major development by the end of fiscal year 2013; however, the additional scope requires additional resources causing the Project's costs to increase. In addition, corrected the end date of a PMO Milestone from 3/3 to 3/30.Also included in this BCR is the request to eliminate a performance measure currently listed on the Investment's E300.  The performance measure indicates the Investment would conduct an independent customer survey of users reporting the GWA Way; however, due to an organizational realignment, the resources to establish and conduct the survey are no longer available to the Investment. CARS will continue to use the annual consolidated FMS Survey to evaluate its customer performance. Revision Reason: Rebaseline - scope and objectives evolve due to incremental or iterative system development
Comment: This baseline change is requested to re-plan existing activities, extend the current baseline schedule for the CARS from September 2013 to June 2014, and incorporate the additional projects and associated milestones and budget associated with the proposed scope. The additional projects proposed are:Central Accounting Reporting Interface (CARI) 3.1,Budget Reporting Service (BRS 1.0),Agency Standard Reports (ASR) 2.2,ASR 2.3,Bank Transaction Module (BTM) 3.1,  andCARS System of Record (SoR).The re-planning of existing activities includes: 1)the need to respond to system requirements under the Straight Through Processing (STP) initiative; 2)the need to de-conflict testing efforts due to technical dependencies related to the implementation of CARS as the System of Record (SoR) and resource constraints, attributed to availability of the test environment  and module specific subject matter experts; and3)the need to accommodate technical dependencies inherent in the way CARS has been planned, designed, and developed for the START project to serve as the final production release. As a result, upon identification of the requirement to incorporate functionality that will allow agencies to maintain their current methods of budgetary reporting, the START project implementation date had to be pushed back ~ 9 months.The original CARS baseline did provide all stakeholders requirements to complete the transition from STAR to CARS including the revision and elimination of the STAR interfaces and execution of a comprehensive system wide test. Addition CARI releases to change all interfaces from the legacy system - STAR to CARS and to implement requested features that enable the Fiscal Projection System (nFPS) to align existing processes of budgetary reporting to the Monthly Treasury Statement once produced from the CARS.The BRS and ASR modules required additional releases to migrate remaining STAR reports to CARS and  implement the MTS Line Code in the data structures and in existing MTS reports developed in ASR 2.1.  Adding the MTS Line Code to CARS allows OMB, CBO, USAID, Ed and others to avoid extensive modifications to their systems to perform budgetary reporting.  Provide the capability to research and review account changes and posted transactions for the current accounting period and up to 5 years and prior (MTS Line Analysis).

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: CDC OID National Healthcare Safety Network (NHSN)
Comment: The overall status of the NHSN project is on task, the project continues to meet the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) deadlines while balancing requested functionality from its user population.  The roles and responsibilities of the Surveillance Branch, Division of Healthcare Quality Promotion (DHQP), NCEZID, are expanding rapidly because of legislated healthcare reporting requirements and burgeoning working relationships between the Surveillance Branch and the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) and State Departments of Health.  At both the federal and state levels, this rapidly expanding portfolio of work involves much greater use of the National Healthcare Safety Network (NHSN), a surveillance system for which the Surveillance Branch has lead responsibilities.   These developments place a premium on assuring that qualified staffs are in place to support NHSN.   O&M Funding: The baseline cost for O&M changed due to the recent receipt of additional funds from CMS and Affordable Care Act funding. These funds were used to recruit additional staffing to support NHSN. Replan of schedule: Baseline shows that there were two major releases and a scheduled patch planned. The scope of the patch (6.6.1) expanded in order to address several defects in production and the addition of an unexpected change request to meet a new CMS requirement. This changed the velocity of the release from 1 sprint to 5 sprints, resulting in a significant shift in the go-live date. Additionally, the scope of the fall release 6.7 increased to include an additional component to the system for Long Term Care. This in addition to the need to migrate to the secured access management system (SAMS) requires a recertification, thus changing the release increment from 6.7 to 7.0. The replan impacts the name of the release, not the date or velocity of sprints or costs for DME.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Revision Reason: Rebaseline - significant changes in funding level or availability of fund
Comment: The Program Analysis Contractor that supports the Physician Value (PV) Project within the Physician Feedback Program investment has completed the initial Integrated Baseline Review (IBR) and subsequent re-baseline for the Program.  Since then the Program Analysis Contractor received a contract modification (HHSM-500-2007-00014I/000002) to design, develop and implement a Registration system that is critical to the full implementation of the Value Bases Payment Modifier, as required by Section 3007 of the Affordable Care Act. There was an increase in scope and contract value due to the contract modification. Specifically, we are adding Registration module activities, changing the scope of the Help Desk/Inquiry Support activities to better reflect the actual work and re- arranging Work Breakdown Structure elements and control accounts such that research, analysis, design and development activities for two base years can be tracked effectively.  This new information, based on an IBR, will also include detail on the time and resources needed to successfully implement each activity specified in the investment.  In addition, we closed both the Physician Feedback and Physician Value projects within this investment and consolidated them both into the new Physician Value Based Modifier Program project.  This new re-baseline will allow us to accurately manage progress being made in the PV Project within this investment, and accurately plan for work in the option years of the contract.  The pilot ended as started to develop the PV system.  The pilot was a developmental effort that informed how to build the PV system, and the O&M metrics were deactivated as the investment entered full development again.  The PV system is on a 2-year plan, expected to be finished by 9/2014.

Rebaseline with Corrections - The OneTrack CMS project was rebaselined because additional funding was added to account for a change in project scope.

1.  In November\December 2011, SBA accepted the development contractor s proposal which indicated that a content management system (open source) technology would be used at the presentation level which was in response to the GCBD SOW solicitation which stated the contractor shall leverage CASE environment tools but did not overtly preclude the use of open source technology.  GCBD worked to reduce potential contract issues and risks regarding re-engineering of work in progress as well as additional design, analysis, development work and associated delays that are required due to the disapproval of open source technology and the CASE change in strategy presented by the OCIO in April 2012.2.  Since the proposed and accepted content management system was disapproved in April 2012 by OCIO, the GCBD OneTrack CMS development contractor has been directed by OCIO to instead use software development tools native to the .NET platform environment such as Visual Basic, HTML, Visual Studio, etc. to name a few of the possibilities from which to select for the custom development.  This change in strategy has impacted GCBD budgeted funds for work already performed using the content management system strategy and it induced additional cost and schedule impacts.3.  The detailing of the business development requirements yielded additional processes which needed to be vetted and documented.  The additional processes impacted both cost and schedule.4.  Detailed data analysis for the data scrubbing and migration resulted in additional resources and level of work required to complete these activities.  This impacted both the timeline and cost. 5.  Bullet 1 alone had pushed the schedule variance beyond the 30 day delay mark.6.  Based on Bullets 1-5, additional funding was added to the project and the schedule was re-worked to accommodate for the required additional work and finalized in July 2012 thus requiring a new baseline.

GCBD worked to reduce potential contract issues and risks regarding re-engineering of work in progress as well as additional design, analysis, development work and associated delays that are required due to the disapproval of open source technology and the CASE change in strategy presented by the OCIO in April 2012.2.Since the proposed and accepted content management system was disapproved in April 2012 by OCIO, the GCBD OneTrack CMS development contractor, The development contractor has been directed by OCIO to instead use software development tools native to the .NET platform environment such as Visual Basic, HTML, Visual Studio, etc. to name a few of the possibilities from which to select for the custom development.  This change in strategy has impacted GCBD budgeted funds for work already performed using the content management system strategy and it induces additional cost and schedule impacts.3.The detailing of the business development requirements yielded additional processes which needed to be vetted and documented.  The additional processes impacted both cost and schedule.4.Detailed data analysis for the data scrubbing and migration resulted in additional resources and level of work required to complete these activities.  This impacted both the timeline and cost. 5.Bullet 1 alone had pushed the schedule variance beyond the 30 day delay mark.6.Based on Bullets 1-5, the schedule funding was added to the project and the schedule was re-worked to accommodate for the required additional work and finalized on July 2012 thus requiring a new baseline.
