The FATCA registration system will be a web-based application that allows Foreign Financial Institutions (FFIs) to apply for and become a Participating FFI (PFFI), with an agreement between the IRS and Foreign Financial Institutions. It will include a secure online document submission of the FFI registration form, agreement forms, deemed compliance forms as required (including electronic signature), periodic certifications and payment percentages for FFIs and their affiliates.On May 31, 2012, the FATCA Governance Board approved a cost and schedule change for the FFI Registration Project Release 1 to ensure compliance with security requirements.-- Currently developed login procedure did not meet Level 2 security requirements, as the User Confirmation Number appeared on the screen-- New procedure will replace the system assigned User Confirmation Number with a user-generated Access Code.-- For paper registrants and members, a temporary Access Code will be generated, which will be replaced by a user created Access Code during the initial loginThe details about the registration are going to evolve as treaties are negotiated.To meet level 2 security requirements:-- The code, testing and integration activities were increased to code, test and integrate the modifications required by the revised requirements.-- The program management activity increased in cost to continue managing the program until the revised completion date.

Revision Reason: Rebaseline - scope and objectives evolve due to incremental or iterative system development
Comment: Intergovernmental Agreements (IGAs) have driven scope changes to the Foreign Financial Institution (FFI) Registration application schedule for deployment December 2012.  Due to the significance of changes to the scope, development of the FATCA FFI Registration release 1.0 officially ceased November, 2012. The purpose of this BCR is to reflect the change in scope based on agreements reached by the Governance bodies to deliver the legislated functionality.FATCA FFI Registration Release 1.0 was originally intended to develop a web-based application that allows a Foreign Financial Institution (FFI) to apply for and become a Participating FFI (PFFI), with an agreement between the IRS and Foreign Financial Institutions.  The registration system would include a secure online document submission of the FFI registration form, agreement forms, deemed compliance forms as required (including electronic signature), periodic certifications and payment percentages for FFIs and their affiliates.FATCA FFI Registration Release 1.1 will follow the IGA model agreements changing the registration requirements by requiring the Host Country Tax Authorities (HCTAs) to take on increased governance responsibilities; As a result, IRS registration will be redesigned to streamline the registration process with three primary steps: Account Creation, Registration Form and Agreement, and Approval.This BCR establishes the FATCA FFI Registration Release 1.1 to deliver the agreed functionality in two Drops:-- Drop 1 (early July): FFI Registration Release 1.1 Drop 1 will focus on high priority and externally visible requirements-- Drop 2 (early October): will allow the IRS the ability to process FFI Registrations

Comment: This rebaseline consolidates five projects (IT Installations, Overseas Maintenance, Digital Services, OBO NEC/NOB Move Support, and Global Repair Depot) into one new project, the Digital Services Initiative. Four of the projects (IT Installations, Overseas Maintenance, Digital Services, OBO NEC/NOB Move Support) were already included in the investment level baseline, and are being consolidated into this one program. The fifth project, Global Repair Depot, was not included in the investment s WBS, but was receiving funding through the investment s budget office and was aligned under the investment in the portfolio structure. This rebaseline also relocates the Domestic Technical Services (DTS) child submission from the Customer Support Service Line to the Deployment, Maintenance, and Refresh Service Line. In addition to the Global Repair Depot project, this project was not included in the investment s WBS, but was receiving funding through the investment s budget office and was aligned under the investment in the portfolio structure. The inclusion of these two projects in the investment baseline increases the overall lifecycle cost for Deployment, Maintenance and Refresh.

Revision Reason: Rebaseline - other reason consistent with agency policy and M-10-27
Comment: Do Not Pay is requesting a baseline change for FY 13 DME activities due to new legislation that directly impacts the investment's development activities. The Improper Payments Elimination and Recovery Improvement Act of 2012 (IPERIA, PL 112-248) requires all Executive Branch agencies to make pre-award and pre-payment checks through a Do Not Pay Working System by June 1, 2013. The Office of Management and Budget designated Treasury's Do Not Pay investment as a part of the working system identified in the IPERIA legislation. In order to support agencies in meeting this goal, Do Not Pay is leveraging Treasury's access to agency payment data and integrating Do Not Pay into the Treasury payment stream. In order to achieve the initial tight deadline established by IPERIA, the investment must modify in progress and planned projects for FY 13 and beyond. The functionality initially planned for FY 13 will be implemented in application releases over the next two fiscal years.
BCR is required to clear operational metrics to ensure Investment does not trend red/yellow due to data lag reporting times.

The purpose of this Correction BCR is to re-establish the 2013 Target for the Top-3 metrics. In a previous BCR, dated 12/07/2012, Treasury CPIC zeroed out the 2013 Target to ensure investment does not result in a Red (Invalid)operational metric variance before Actual Results are available to report. This Correction BCR will re-establish the 97% for the Top-3 2013 Target originally entered by the investment PM during E300 submission in Sept. 2012.

Revision Reason: Rebaseline - scope and objectives evolve due to incremental or iterative system development
Comment: This BCR is only for FY13 and only includes figures from the beginning of the IPP investment up through FY13. An additional BCR will be submitted for FY14 and beyond.  FY13 benchmarks the beginning of a major scope expansion in IPP with the implementation of the IGT capabilities. This baseline change request is needed for several reasons:  To adequately reflect costs associated with significant changes in scope driven by the Fiscal Service's business vision to:o Enhance IPP intra-gov buy/sell functionality to support DoD in managing their intra-governmental buy/sell business processes more efficiently. o Continue accelerating and increasing the adoption of IPP within the Federal Government and externally with vendor organizations between 2013 -2015The revised baseline reflects costs associated with: o Increase in funding for existing Operations and Maintenance milestones to support an increased number of agencies and vendors for electronic invoicing and the additional business line of intra-governmental buy/sell activity- Develop and Implement market research and competitive intelligence strategy for IPP against other commercial e-invoicing solutions.- Expansion of agency implementation and customer service support for Intra-governmental transactions. - Implementation of a customer relationship management system.- Provide implementation planning assistance to agencies to expedite implementation.- Expansion of vendor enrollment effort, including the rolling out of Payment Notification Service to vendors of non-IPP agencies.o Addition of new DME milestones and resources to existing DME milestones to support the following expanded scope:- Development of new application functionality and automated system interfaces to support exchange o Intra-governmental buy/sell transactions between IPP and systems at DOD service components:- Development of new features for commercial vendor invoicing to enroll new agencies and vendors.- Infrastructure changes driven by TWAI and Fiscal Service- Conversion to the PAM standard format and addition of check and wire payment information to IPP.- Enhancements to meet the standards for retention of electronic records as set forth by the Federal Acquisition Regulation (FAR) and the Federal Records Act.- Expansion of Web Focus reports and additional reporting metrics.

Investment Title: WAPA CSO Cost Recovery BIDSS II
Comment: The BIDSS II project has not yet begun.  The official project initiation and kickoff will be in 1st quarter FY11.  Therefore, the milestones established in the Exhibit 300 submitted in 2009 represented early estimates, which have now been refined over the past year, and the data included in this current Exhibit 300 are more accurate.  Most significantly, the implementation  go-live  to the new system is now planned for the first half of FY13, rather than June 2012.  This has changed the planned start and finish dates of most milestones, as well slightly adjusting upward associated costs, especially in FY13.  Also, improvements have been made to the structure, numbering, and descriptions of the milestones, in accordance with OMB requirements.

Investment Title: WAPA CSO Cost Recovery BIDSS II

Investment Title: WAPA CSO Cost Recovery BIDSS II
Comment: This investment has recently rebaselined its project plan.  The start date will be delayed from FY 11 Q1 to FY FY11 Q3 due to several key business factors:  1) The Western STRIPES implementation project has taken longer than initially scheduled but will be completed by April 2011; 2) Several key preparatory initiatives for BIDSS and interfaced systems could be completed before the BIDSS II project begins, lowering risk by reducing complexity of the upgrade; 3) The preparation, solicitation, and award of the consultant contract supporting the BIDSS II upgrade will not be completed until mid-2011; 4) Additional project analysis and planning is being done to ensure that the BIDSS II project, including the project schedule, is business value driven. Therefore, to reflect this delayed start, changes need to be made in the Cost and Schedule Performance Table, specifically start dates for FY11 milestones. The go-live date for the new system is still planned for mid- FY13.

Investment Title: WAPA CSO Cost Recovery BIDSS II
Comment: The BIDSS II project has not yet begun, and Western has determined to delay the start from the first quarter of FY11 to the third quarter of FY11 due to several key business factors: 1) The Western STRIPES implementation project has taken longer than initially scheduled but will substantially completed by April 2011; 2) Several key preparatory initiatives for BIDSS and interfaced systems could be completed before the BIDSS II project begins, lowering risk by reducing complexity of the upgrade; 3) The preparation, solicitation, and award of the consultant contract supporting the BIDSS II upgrade will not be completed until mid-2011; 4) Additional project analysis and planning is being done to ensure that the BIDSS II project, including the project schedule, is business value driven. Therefore, to reflect this delayed start, changes need to be made in the Cost and Schedule Performance Table, specifically start dates for FY11 milestones. For this rebaselining, milestone dates in FY11 and FY12 are not being changed, and implementation go-live to the new system is still planned for mid- FY13. An Integrated Baseline Review will be conducted in conjunction with approval of CD-1 prior to the project kickoff.

The follow-on assessment tool, originally to be called RAMP 2G, is currently early in the requirements definition stage and original milestones chosen are no longer valid. These operational performance measures included are common across the legacy RAMP v1.3 and MIST projects.  Deactivated measures were original measures established in October 2011, but proved to be invalid measures of operational performance.  Additional measures or updated benchmarks will be proposed once the follow-on assessment tool project as received ADE-2A approval.

The solution sets include pre-acquisition activities scoped by individual projects designed to inform operational and technical requirements. The concept and the requirements maturity is used to inform acquisition decisions. When the FAA makes a decision to acquire new systems, those acquisitions are represented in their individual OMB-300s . Therefore, the information in the solution set OMB-300s represents the planned pre-implementation activities for the applicable timeframe. Due to the incremental development approach, designed to reduce overall programmatic risk, the solution set OMB-300s are planning in nature and will remain in planning. Section II.B milestones have been updated to reflect funding changes as of January 7, 2011. Milestones have also been broken out into greater detail consistent with FAA plans to improve milestone clarity and transparency.

NextGen CATMT WP 2 was baselined by a Final Investment Decision (FID) on 9/26/2008 and Work Package 3 was baselined by a FID on 1/26/2010.The reporting of TFM and NextGen CATMT Workpackages as two separate investments did not rebaseline (change costs or schedule) of either the TFM nor the CATMT portion of the investments. This BCR was approved by the Treasury CIO on December 30, 2010. The BCR modifies the O and M and DME milestones for FY2011 through FY2015.  Milestones FY2012 through FY2015 were added.  Funding for FY2011 has increased by $3.914M.  The funding increase is in three areas.  The first is the hiring of 13 new FTE's in support of ACS.  The hiring will be done in two different phases.  The first is to do a contractor to federal (C2F) conversion as a cost saving effort, a maximum of 5 FTE.  ACS will also fill a needed training position from the Federal Career Intern Program (FCIP).  There will be a transition of the ACSWeb application to the government once ACSWeb is rewritten.  Four Java FTEs will be added during FY2011 year.  Lastly, the Testing area has also increased their FTE base as a result of the additional testing needed for the ACSWeb rewrite.  The Testing area added 3 more FTE.    The second reason is increased contractor funding for the ACSWeb rewrite.  The ACSWeb rewrite will provide a replacement of the Attachmate Presentation Builder to Veristream Bridge Integrator.  ACS does not currently posses the knowledge to transition ACSWeb operation and maintenance once it is rewritten.  ACS has very limited knowledge of the ACSWeb application. This BCR is being submitted to reflect: 1) FY 2012 Budget Pass-back funding reduction - The FY 2012 budget pass-back cut $3.2M for application development and maintenance contractor support. The cut is assumed to extend through the project life cycle.  Total life cycle costs were reduced by $51.8M, of which $25.9M is contractor costs.  As mitigation, FIRST is adding two technical FTE resources, and training three existing technical FTE resources in Java development. 2)Elimination of baseline cost risk adjustments - The current baseline provided for cost risk adjustments based upon a comprehensive risk analysis.  Having gained experience and confidence with GTAS on the TWAI platform, and recognizing the realities of the current budget environment, the FIRST project team concluded that no additional resources are likely to be provided in the foreseeable future, and risk adjustments going forward will be to functional scope and performance, not cost increases.  Inflation factors were also changed to the latest A-94 Appendix C nominal interest rates.  Elimination of the risk adjustment and change in the inflation factors resulted in a decrease of $14.9M from life cycle costs.3) Elimination of GFRS Oracle license fees - The BPD/FMS Fiscal IT platform support will assume responsibility for GFRS's Oracle license fees.  This reduces project life cycle costs by $5.7M.4)Changes in scope and individual milestones - As a result of the loss of contractor funding, the FIRST project team reevaluated the scope of GTAS and made the following schedule and cost adjustments:a)Reduced from three to one the number of GTAS post-implementation enhancement releasesb)Redesigned scope so that GTAS provides GFRS with ATB data summarized by line item instead of providing detailed USSGL-based ATB datac)Reduced the scope of GTAS's management reportsd)Scaled back GTAS functionality to temporarily delete USSGL guidance information e)Redefined and rescheduled the final two preproduction GTAS development releases based upon functional scope and resource changes, with Release 4.0 starting April 4, 2011f)Added four GFRS development releases for its enhancements, beginning April 4, 2011g)Life cycle FTE costs were reduced by $1.7M and non-FTE, non-contractor, costs were reduced by $3.6M.5)Milestone Corrections - Correction to 100% actual % complete for 3 milestones closed early in the 2010 BCR, as the EVM metrics are distorted.

Investment Title: Web Currency Banking and Retrieval System (WebCBRS)
Comment: This BCR has been approved by the Treasury CIO, 11/10/2010WebCBRS submitted a baseline change for two reasons: First, FinCEN was given approval by Treasury and OMB to move forward on their BSA IT Modernization system, which will replace WebCBRS as the System of Record for BSA data.  Further, a decision was made by IRS, FinCEN, Treasury and OMB executives in May 2010 that WebCBRS would remain operational within IRS and be the recipient of BSA data from FinCEN's BSA IT Modernization system.  WebCBRS will continue to be maintained and used within IRS for Title 26 tax processing (8300s, Excise, Penalties) and BSA Case processing by CI and SBSE. This is investment is being moved from Mixed Life Cycle to a Steady State status. All future maintenance activities are specifically related to legislative changes, sustaining operations and system hardware/software upgrades (rust replacement.)No further enhancements to the system are planned. The second reason is with the movement of the system to Steady State, and a reduction in the WebCBRS DP services budget, contractor support is being phased out effective FY2011. Beginning October 1, 2010, the project will be positioned to resume full responsibility for all activities associated with the WebCBRS Steady State processing with only government FTEs. It should be noted, however, that though there is a decrease in costs with the elimination of the contractors, many maintenance functions were placed on hold over the last year, due to the Mainframe Migration and transition of all applications from ECC-Detroit to ECC-Martinsburg. There are over two hundred Data Quality items that were not addressed during this period, as well as other requests and issues due to legislative changes. These requests and changes are expected to continue through the life cycle of the project. As a result, the government FTEs originally aligned to support DME enhancements have been realigned to support the Steady State and sustaining operations work.

Treasury's initial Enterprise Content Management (ECM) approach to address mission/business needs was based on a large and expensive system that was submitted to OMB in a business case in FY2009. OMB imposed a funding constraint due to the high cost to deploy and too slow to yield tangible results. Capabilities were limited to Document Management, Records Management, and Case Workflow Management at the Terrorism and Financial Intelligence (TFI) offices. Expansion to other Treasury bureaus and implementation of Electronic Knowledge Content Management and Records Management Archive capabilities were deferred. Treasury contracted MITRE to perform a study that determined that a more modular approach to content management should be piloted at IRS-CI, OFAC, and FinCEN. The selected alternative was a Joint Development/Separate Deployment option for $63.6M with IRS-CI responsible for the first pilot deployment. OMB denied a IRS-CI TEOAF request to support the Investigative Scanning & Document Management (ISDM) pilot resulting in the discontinuation of the IDSM project. Per OMB direction, Treasury engaged Gartner to conduct an independent assessment of ECM to provide recommended strategies for an enterprise-wide content management system. Based on OMB guidance and results of the Gartner study, Treasury has determined that a scaled-down shared services approach with user provisioning and a well-structured governance model was required to meet the content management needs of the Bureaus and Departmental offices. The ECM IT initiative strategically unifies Treasury capabilities to electronically capture, store, search/analyze, share and manage documents. Treasury's new strategy for the ECM program is comprised of multiple document management projects, which are part of a scalable enterprise-wide initiative. ECM will provide the Department of the Treasury with the following functionalities: Correspondence Tracking, FOIA/e-Discovery, Collaboration, Evidence Management, Case Management, Paper Reduction, and an underlying Basic Content Services (BCS) Technology and Records Management foundation. The capabilities provided are built on the platform most suited for the business requirement -SharePoint 2010.  As a result of this new funding strategy, a BCR needs to be submitted to report against the most accurate (and current) baseline.

The continued need for the Licensing Support Network depends on the continuation of NRC review of DOE's license application for Yucca Mountain, which in turn depends on:   (a) the Commission's decision on the recent ASLB ruling denying DOE's motion to withdraw its license application for Yucca Mountain, which is now under Commission review; (b) the outcome of anticipated Court of Appeals review of that Commission decision, as well as the outcome of a pending Court of Appeals review raising related challenges to DOE's withdrawal request;  and (c) the availability of funds.   Further, in response to NRC inquiries, DOE has committed to maintaining the LSN availability of its HLW document collection, which constitutes 98.9 percent of the documents available on the system, through the conclusion of the Court of Appeals review process outlined in item (b) above.  If the outcome of those appeals sustains the ASLB decision to deny DOE's motion to withdraw its license application, and if Congress provides the necessary funding, the NRC would continue its licensing review and associated adjudicatory proceedings in accordance with the Nuclear Waste Policy Act, as amended, and pursuant to the NRC's regulations.  In that case, the LSN would need to continue operation during the NRC adjudicatory process and probably though any review by the Court of Appeals.  In light of this potential continuing need, NRC has awarded a new LSN operations and maintenance contract (base year plus four one-year options) extending through 2015 and extending the operations of this system through 2015.
